instruction: [INST] Analyze this file to learn MacBook motherboard repair. The 'definitions' section explains key technical terms. The 'threads' section contains real-world repair discussions. Use both sections to understand and learn how to troubleshoot MacBook issues. Posts from username 'larossmann' , 'dukefawks' , and '2informaticos' are posts from trusted experts.[/INST]

definitions.A1466: What is A1466? A1466 is a model number for a 13 inch size MacBook Air from years Early 2015, 2017, Mid 2012, Mid 2013, Early 2014 with EMC 2925, that may contain one of these boards depending on the year & configuration: 820-00165, 820-3209, 820-3437..
definitions.820-3437: What is 820-3437? a LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER.
definitions.PPBUS_S5_HS_COMPUTING_ISNS: What is PPBUS_S5_HS_COMPUTING_ISNS? This power rail is PPBUS_G3H after going through a current sense resistor that sits between PPBUS_G3H & the input of PPBUS_G3H to circuitry that provides power for the CPU..
definitions.U1950: What is U1950? This chip often becomes corroded on pin 8 on the PP3V42_G3H pin causing PM_SLP_S4_L to go missing.
definitions.ALL_SYS_PWRGD: What is ALL_SYS_PWRGD? ALL_SYS_PWRGD is present when PP1V8_S3, PP5V_S3, PP1V2_S3, PP1V05_S0, PP5V_S0, PP3V3_S0, & PP1V5_S0 are present and working. If any of these rails is not working, ALL_SYS_PWRGD will be pulled down and the machine will not turn on. .
definitions.PLT_RESET_L: What is PLT_RESET_L? PLT_RESET_L is platform reset, this signal keeps the system from POSTing. _L means the signal is asserted when its voltage is low. .

threads.title: <MACBOOK MODEL NUMBER>A1466</MACBOOK MODEL NUMBER> <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-3437</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>-B no power
threads.message:
Hi,

I have an <MACBOOK MODEL NUMBER>A1466</MACBOOK MODEL NUMBER> <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-3437</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>-B, that has fan spin, green light, but no power on. It gets to 250mA.

<SIGNAL>PPBUS_S5_HS_COMPUTING_ISNS</SIGNAL> has 0.135 on diode reading, witch seams to be very low (compared with other board, but not sure if ok), and 8.59V. 

Can you help?

threads.title: <MACBOOK MODEL NUMBER>A1466</MACBOOK MODEL NUMBER> <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-3437</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>-B no power
threads.message:
"<SIGNAL>PPBUS_S5_HS_COMPUTING_ISNS</SIGNAL> has 0.135 on diode reading, witch seams to be very low"
Not true!
Keep in mind, <TRANSISTOR>Q7130</TRANSISTOR> has a internal Schottky dioded added on the low-side; consult the schematic.

Which big coils get voltage?
Also check <SIGNAL>ALL_SYS_PWRGD</SIGNAL> level.
Inspect <CHIP>U1950</CHIP> for corrosion.

threads.title: <MACBOOK MODEL NUMBER>A1466</MACBOOK MODEL NUMBER> <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-3437</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>-B no power
threads.message:
Hi,
TKS.

<SIGNAL>ALL_SYS_PWRGD</SIGNAL> = 3.3V

<CHIP>U1950</CHIP> had a bit of corrosion and so I've replaced it (but with same result).

L7310 = 1.7V
L7320 = 1.7V
L7630 = 1.0V
L7430 = 1.2V
L7560 = 3.3V
L7520 = 5.1V
L7130 = 8.59V

L7701 = 0V
L3095 = 0V

threads.message:
Check all resistors and coils from page 11.
Also check all SPI Bus Termination resistors and their traces.
Clean J6100, if looks dirty/corroded.

Try known good BIOS.
